Chapter 2: The Perimeter
The wind at the edge of the Sector 7 Breach Zone didn't blow; it vibrated. It carried a metallic tang that sat heavy on the tongue, the unmistakable scent of "Void-rot."
"Stay behind the yellow lines!" a voice crackled through a megaphone.
A line of students stood at the edge of a massive concrete overlook. Below them, a section of the old city was trapped in a translucent, grey dome. Inside, the buildings looked like melting wax, frozen in mid-collapse.
"Look at the density readings on the main gate," Mira whispered, nudging Ren. She was clutching her sensor-staff so hard her knuckles were white. "It’s a Grade 3 Breach. Why did they bring us this close?"
"Data collection," Ren replied, his eyes fixed on a group of veteran Hunters at the base of the overlook. They were loading heavy, jagged harpoons into an armored transport. "The Association needs 'baseline stress levels' from students. We’re the control group."
"Control group for what?" Jax grunted, stepping up behind them. He looked pale, despite his bravado. "It’s just a cage. The Voids can't get through the Veil. Right, Ren? Tell us what your little screen says."
Ren looked down at his handheld. The screen was flickering, lines of text jumping erratically. "The Veil is holding. But the atmospheric pressure inside the dome is dropping. That usually means a 'Breach-Lurk' is feeding."
"Feeding on what?" Mira asked, her voice trembling. "There's nothing alive in there."
Ren didn't answer. He was watching a man sitting on a crate near the transport. It was Old Man Hobs, a veteran Scavenger with a prosthetic arm made of dull, unpolished iron. Hobs caught Ren’s eye and made a subtle motion—two fingers tapped against his temple, then pointed toward the grey dome.
"Look at the shadows," Hobs shouted over the wind, his voice raspy. He wasn't talking to the teachers; he was talking to the wind. "The Association tells you they’re monsters. But have you ever seen a monster that knows how to hide in a reflection?"
"Ignore the Scavenger!" Professor Aris called out, walking down the line of students. Her long coat fluttered in the jagged wind. "He’s spent too much time breathing unfiltered Void-mist. Focus on the shimmer of the Veil. Tell me, Kaelen, what do you see?"
Kaelen stood at the very edge, his eyes glowing with a faint, inner light. "The Essence flow is rhythmic. 4.4 cycles per second. It’s stable. A perfect containment."
"Stable," Aris repeated, her voice unreadable. She glanced at Ren. "And you, Ren? No Essence to guide you. What do you see with those eyes of yours?"
Ren looked at the grey city. He didn't see the rhythm Kaelen saw. He saw the way the shadows of the melting buildings seemed to move against the light.
"The shadows are taller than the buildings," Ren said quietly.
Jax laughed, a harsh, forced sound. "The Zero’s seeing ghosts now. Great. Maybe the 'Static' finally fried his brain."
Suddenly, a high-pitched alarm wailed from the Hunter transport below. The veteran Hunters scrambled.
"Status!" a commander yelled.
"Spike in the core!" a voice screamed back over the radio. "The Veil is—it’s not breaking, it’s inhaling!"
The grey dome suddenly pulsed. For a split second, the translucent barrier turned pitch black. The students screamed as the vibration in the air turned into a physical pressure, slamming into their chests.
"Back! Get back to the buses!" Professor Aris shouted, her calm demeanor vanishing.
As the students turned to run, Ren stayed frozen for a second. He saw it—a thin, black thread of smoke snaking out from the 'stable' Veil, darting toward the overlook. It didn't go for Kaelen, the highest rank. It didn't go for Jax.
It flickered toward Ren’s feet, disappearing into his shadow just as the teachers pushed the students toward the transport.
"Ren! Move!" Mira grabbed his arm, pulling him toward the bus.
Ren stumbled, his heart hammering against his ribs. He looked at his handheld scanner. The screen wasn't flickering anymore. It was dead. Completely black.
"Did you feel that?" Mira gasped as they scrambled onto the bus. "The pressure? It felt like... like something was looking at us."
"It was just a fluctuation," Kaelen said from the front of the bus, though his hands were shaking as he adjusted his gloves. "The Association will have it recalibrated by tonight."
Ren sat in the back, staring at his shadow on the floor of the bus. In the dim light, his shadow looked darker than it should. Sharper.
He reached into his pocket and felt the small, unlabeled metal disc the janitor had slipped him earlier. It was ice cold.
